stephen gendin an activist and writer who founded a nationally known mail order prescription service for people infected with hiv died wednesday in new york he was 34 mr gendin died of cardiac arrest while undergoing chemotherapy for aids related lymphoma said sean strubb founder of poz a national magazine about life with aids mr gendin spent the last 15 years working to help people who had aids or who were infected with hiv the virus that causes it he was a founder and the chief executive of the community prescription service a mail order pharmacy service that also distributes information to people with aids mr gendin also became known through a regular column he wrote for poz in the column he discussed in graphic detail the toll aids took on his body his fantasies of political assassination and in an article that incited outrage among many gay men the guilt and the pleasure he felt from having unprotected sex as a freshman at brown university mr gendin learned he was infected with hiv he founded the rhode island chapter of act up the aids protest group and was active in fund raising for the organization 's new york chapter he regularly took part in protests rallies and mass acts of civil disobedience for which he had a long arrest record he was a director of aid for aids which distributes medications to patients in latin america he was also a founder of sex panic a group that contends it is preserving new york 's untrammeled sexual culture mr gendin is survived by his partner kyle macdowell his father sidney gendin of ypsilanti mich and his sister margo hart of ionia mich

